_source.title: Syslog Intro
_source.visState:
{"title":"Syslog Intro","type":"markdown","params":{"markdown":"Use [the Syslog Dashboard](#/dashboard/Syslog-Dashboard) to explore this data

Syslog data is loaded via the following methods:
* Files in the `/logstash/syslog/` directory.
  * NOTE: Create e.g. `/logstash/syslog/2015/` for files that should be loaded as if they are from the year 2015.
* Network syslog messages sent to UDP or TCP port 5514
  * NOTE: Open the firewall ports using the `fw_modify.sh` script.  For example:
    * `fw_modify.sh -a open -p 5514 -r udp`
    * `fw_modify.sh -a open -p 5514 -r tcp`
    * [filebeat](https://www.elastic.co/products/beats/filebeat) messages sent to TCP 5044
  * NOTE: Open the firewall ports using the `fw_modify.sh` script.  For example:
    * `fw_modify.sh -a open -p 5044 -r tcp`
    * Network RELP messages sent to TCP 5516
  * NOTE: Open firewall ports using the `fw_modify.sh` script.  For example:
    * `fw_modify.sh -a open -p 5516 -r tcp`"},"aggs":[],"listeners":{}}

NetFlow Intro
_source.visState:
{"title":"NetFlow Intro","type":"markdown","params":{"markdown":"Use [the NetFlow Dashboard](#/dashboard/NetFlow-Dashboard) to explore this data

NetFlow data is loaded via the following methods:
* NetFlow v5 network messages sent to UDP port 9995
  * NOTE: Open the firewall ports using the `fw_modify.sh` script.  For example:
    * `fw_modify.sh -a open -p 9995 -r udp`
    * Files in the `/logstash/nfarch/` directory.
  * NOTE: Files must be in CSV format, created with the following `nfdump` command: `nfdump (-r <input file> | -R <input dir>) -q -N -O tstart -o "fmt:$EXP_IP %das %dmk %eng %ts %fl 0 %byt %pkt %in %da %nh %sa %dp %sp %te %out %pr 0 0 %sas %smk %stos %flg 0"`, where `$EXP_IP` is the IP address of the NetFlow exporter. (Use `0.0.0.0` if needed, but this field is required.)"},"aggs":[],"listeners":{}}

_source.title: SOF-ELK VM Intro
_source.visState:
{"title":"SOF-ELK VM Intro","type":"markdown","params":{"markdown":"## Welcome to the SOF-ELK (Security Operations and Forensics Elasticsearch/Logstash/Kibana) distribution

This VMware image was created with a fully functional ELK configuration.  The VM will ingest various log formats, and includes several dashboards to present the data in useful formats.  While this version of the VM was created specifically for the SANS DFIR FOR572 class, it is maintained as community resource.

See the blocks at the bottom of this page to learn more about which types of data the VM is preconfigured to ingest and how to feed it.

You probably want to see the dashboards, though - here are the three we've pre-built for the VM:

[Syslog Dashboard](#/dashboard/Syslog-Dashboard) | [NetFlow Dashboard](#/dashboard/NetFlow-Dashboard) | [HTTPD Log Dashboard](#/dashboard/HTTPD-Log-Dashboard)"},"aggs":[],"listeners":{}}

_source.title: HTTPD Log Intro
_source.visState:
{"title":"HTTPD Log Intro","type":"markdown","params":{"markdown":"Use [the HTTPD Log Dashboard](#/dashboard/HTTPD-Log-Dashboard) to explore this data

HTTPD log data is loaded via the following methods:
* Files in the `/logstash/httpd/` directory
  * NOTE: Logs in the Common, Combined, and Combined + VHost formats are currently supported
* Network syslog messages sent to UDP or TCP port 5515
  * NOTE: Open the firewall ports using the `fw_modify.sh` script.  For example:
    * `fw_modify.sh -a open -p 5515 -r udp`
    * `fw_modify.sh -a open -p 5515 -r tcp`
    * Network RELP messages sent to TCP 5517
  * NOTE: Open firewall ports using the `fw_modify.sh` script.  For example:
    * `fw_modify.sh -a open -p 5517 -r tcp`"},"aggs":[],"listeners":{}}
